00:42:30.180 --> 00:42:33.049
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Thank you so much for the presentation.

00:42:33.049 --> 00:42:34.200
That was wonderful.

00:42:34.200 --> 00:42:37.950
You talked a lot about accountable giving
and knowing where your dollars are going.

00:42:37.950 --> 00:42:43.400
I'd be curious if you could provide some comments
on indices or benchmarks or types of metrics

00:42:43.400 --> 00:42:47.450
people are able to look at when really knowing
where their dollars are going.

00:42:47.450 --> 00:42:53.559
&gt;&gt;Laura Arrillaga-Andreessen: It's a fantastic
question and a question that every single

00:42:53.559 --> 00:42:59.859
person I know in the philanthropic sector,
myself included, struggles with every single

00:42:59.859 --> 00:43:00.859
day.

00:43:00.859 --> 00:43:09.619
One of the trickiest parts about metrics for
giving is the fact that it is virtually impossible

00:43:09.619 --> 00:43:17.710
to create generalized metrics even across
social issue areas because every non-profit

00:43:17.710 --> 00:43:21.599
organization has a unique model.

00:43:21.599 --> 00:43:31.619
What I can say is that, for you as an individual
philanthropist, if you've seen one non-profit

00:43:31.619 --> 00:43:34.670
you've seen one non-profit and that is it.

00:43:34.670 --> 00:43:40.950
So every non-profit you will need to do research
on yourself.

00:43:40.950 --> 00:43:42.410
[pause]

00:43:42.410 --> 00:43:50.839
There, so there are lots of different online
assessment tools that are, assessment organizations

00:43:50.839 --> 00:43:52.529
that have been created.

00:43:52.529 --> 00:44:00.210
There's GuideStar, GreatNonprofits, Philanthropedia,
GiveWell just to name a few.

00:44:00.210 --> 00:44:07.789
I would encourage you though, for every non-profit
that you're making a gift if that gift is

00:44:07.789 --> 00:44:15.859
significant to you, I would go and read their
annual report or even better, read their 990

00:44:15.859 --> 00:44:22.890
report so you can see exactly how their finances
are breaking down.

00:44:22.890 --> 00:44:30.410
Anybody who claims that having minimal overheard
is a sign of an effectively run non-profit,

00:44:30.410 --> 00:44:33.960
I believe, does not know what they're talking
about.

00:44:33.960 --> 00:44:40.559
There are grass roots advocacy organizations
that are going to have upwards of 80 percent

00:44:40.559 --> 00:44:45.079
of overhead and that's gonna be fine for that
particular model.

00:44:45.079 --> 00:44:51.940
Then there are major endowed institutions
who technically are not gonna have any expenses

00:44:51.940 --> 00:44:58.170
every year that they have to raise through
overhead line items.

00:44:58.170 --> 00:45:02.450
Again it's totally specific; I think specific
to the non-profit.

00:45:02.450 --> 00:45:12.339
I think that if an organization cannot tell
you specifically what success looks like in

00:45:12.339 --> 00:45:17.930
the short term and the intermediate term and
in the long term, that is how they know if

00:45:17.930 --> 00:45:23.079
they're achieving their mission, then I would
not invest in that organization.

00:45:23.079 --> 00:45:30.240
You should be able to easily answer the three
following questions: how many, how deeply,

00:45:30.240 --> 00:45:31.240
how much?

00:45:31.240 --> 00:45:39.569
So how many people are being touched, how
deeply are they being touched by a specific

00:45:39.569 --> 00:45:45.549
dollar amount, that is how holistic is the
approach of this particular non-profit, and

00:45:45.549 --> 00:45:55.349
how much does it cost them to serve each individual
life that they aspire to transform?

00:45:55.349 --> 00:46:02.019
And finally, I think that just as leadership
plays a critically important role, actually

00:46:02.019 --> 00:46:06.509
two final points, just as leadership plays
a critically important role in the for profit

00:46:06.509 --> 00:46:09.940
sector, the same is absolutely true of non-profits.

00:46:09.940 --> 00:46:16.640
So I invest in some non-profits who have extraordinary
leaders even when their particular mission

00:46:16.640 --> 00:46:21.519
and isuary is totally outside of my area of
passion.

00:46:21.519 --> 00:46:29.690
And then also I think it's so critically important
that every non-profit involves their ultimate

00:46:29.690 --> 00:46:37.390
customer, that is the people who benefit from
the services, in the creation of whatever

00:46:37.390 --> 00:46:42.440
their service model is; so involving the customers
in the products.

00:46:42.440 --> 00:46:49.349
Winnie was just telling me that Google's holiday
gift to all the employees was the new phone

00:46:49.349 --> 00:46:56.569
that you guys have which my beloved actually
got on Friday and is incredibly excited about.

00:46:56.569 --> 00:47:06.200
But what's so cool about that strategic corporate
gift is Google now has the feedback loop of

00:47:06.200 --> 00:47:11.859
individuals who would be in their customer
base in terms of what features work well,

00:47:11.859 --> 00:47:16.539
what isn't working well, what's appealing,
what isn't appealing, what's useless, what's

00:47:16.539 --> 00:47:17.539
useful.

00:47:17.539 --> 00:47:21.490
The same needs to be true of how non-profits
create their products.

00:47:21.490 --> 00:47:23.920
That was a very short answer --

00:47:23.920 --> 00:47:24.920
[laughter]

00:47:24.920 --> 00:47:25.920
to that simple question.

