00:47:52.130 --> 00:47:53.130
who all --

00:47:53.130 --> 00:47:54.130
&gt;&gt;Laura Arrillaga-Andreessen: Yeah.

00:47:54.130 --> 00:47:55.209
&gt;&gt;Female #3: equally have an urgent requirement.

00:47:55.209 --> 00:47:58.430
It's very hard to understand where you make
the most impact.

00:47:58.430 --> 00:47:59.930
&gt;&gt;Laura Arrillaga-Andreessen: Thank you.

00:47:59.930 --> 00:48:05.799
So I believe I read about a week ago in the
New York Times or the Wall Street Journal

00:48:05.799 --> 00:48:16.740
that last year alone natural disasters and
catastrophes totaled about 300, it's either

00:48:16.740 --> 00:48:24.299
300, and I know this is a huge different,
or 390, Zack to you remember, billion dollars

00:48:24.299 --> 00:48:31.069
in damage which is obviously in excess of
all philanthropic dollars that were given

00:48:31.069 --> 00:48:32.630
in the United States.

00:48:32.630 --> 00:48:37.319
I think it's really important when you're
approaching philanthropy that you think of

00:48:37.319 --> 00:48:39.809
it in terms of a portfolio.

00:48:39.809 --> 00:48:45.739
And I think the most significant amount of
that portfolio should be driven by your personal

00:48:45.739 --> 00:48:46.739
passion.

00:48:46.739 --> 00:48:54.109
That being said, I also think it's really
valuable to have a friends' fund where you

00:48:54.109 --> 00:48:59.059
allocate a certain percentage of what you're
gonna give every year to what friends and

00:48:59.059 --> 00:49:03.279
co-workers etcetera want you to share with
them.

00:49:03.279 --> 00:49:10.259
But I also think it's important, if emergency
services and disaster relief is not your personal

00:49:10.259 --> 00:49:18.549
passion, I think it's important to allow for
space in your giving portfolio for those needs

00:49:18.549 --> 00:49:28.690
because the reality is when a natural disaster
happens or when a man-made disaster happens

00:49:28.690 --> 00:49:38.440
or when an individual is attacked or a woman
is raped or a house burns down, that is the

00:49:38.440 --> 00:49:42.079
greatest equalizer in our world.

00:49:42.079 --> 00:49:50.440
Like, it does not matter who you are, where
you work, what education you have, we are

00:49:50.440 --> 00:49:53.119
all equal in that situation.

00:49:53.119 --> 00:50:02.460
And I, personally, believe that emergency
services and disaster relief is a critical

00:50:02.460 --> 00:50:08.950
component of what we all should be doing;
it's actually the primary issue area that

00:50:08.950 --> 00:50:17.020
my beloved and I fund with our philanthropy,
primarily because it's the single most underfunded

00:50:17.020 --> 00:50:23.549
area in medicine, in institutional medicine.

00:50:23.549 --> 00:50:31.900
But I always encourage everyone to participate,
but do so only through pre-vetted institutions.

00:50:31.900 --> 00:50:37.339
So if you choose to give to the Red Cross
do so with full awareness of the fact that

00:50:37.339 --> 00:50:42.160
the Red Cross when it's raising money for
any given disaster will be keeping a portion

00:50:42.160 --> 00:50:48.710
of that money so that it has immediate funds
that can get right into the hands of the people

00:50:48.710 --> 00:50:52.719
that need them the most when the next disaster
happens.

00:50:52.719 --> 00:51:00.719
Another great way to meet core community needs
and critical needs through a very secure --

00:51:00.719 --> 00:51:04.479
[pause]

00:51:04.479 --> 00:51:10.269
pre-vetted type of organization is giving
through local community foundations.

00:51:10.269 --> 00:51:16.410
So when Hurricane Katrina happened or --

00:51:16.410 --> 00:51:20.240
[pause]

00:51:20.240 --> 00:51:26.599
when 9/11 happened it was the United Way of
New York City and the New York Community Trust

00:51:26.599 --> 00:51:30.329
that came together and created the September
11th Fund.

00:51:30.329 --> 00:51:37.729
And that ultimately was one of the most, was
probably the most successful effort that met

00:51:37.729 --> 00:51:44.709
not only short term but also immediate term
needs for that particular crisis and did so

00:51:44.709 --> 00:51:47.930
in a way that broadly defined who the victims
were.

